\begin_layout Standard
In three dimensions, there is a point in a plane nearest any point/vector
 not in that plane.
 That point occurs exactly at the projection of the vector onto the plane
 (and that plane is a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

).
 Again, projection is best viewed as projecting a vector onto a subspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this in mind, we have to address the questions of (i) how to project
 a vector onto a subspace of dimension greater than one and (ii) whether
 that projection is always the nearest point/vector within the subspace.
 A lot of this work has already been done, but there is a bit more to do
 now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{p}\}$
\end_inset

 be an orthogonal basis for a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of an inner product space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then the 
\series bold
orthogonal projection
\series default
 of any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{proj}_{W}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{proj}_{W}\mathbf{v}=\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{1}}\mathbf{v}+\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{2}}\mathbf{v}+\cdots+\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{p}}\mathbf{v}.
\]

\end_inset

Because each projection is a multiple of one of the basis elements, this
 is a linear combination of the basis elements and therefore lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Next, we will need some terminology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of an inner product space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to every vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
orthogonal
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
orthogonal
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
orthogonal complement
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
orthogonal!complement
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 (read 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 perp
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Can you show that 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:is-a-vector-space"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal for any vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 of an inner product space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Orthogonalization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we can now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}-\text{proj}_{W}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of an inner product space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{p}\}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\shape italic
orthogonal basis
\shape default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
basis!orthogonal
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\langle\mathbf{v}-\text{proj}_{W}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\rangle & =\left\langle \mathbf{v}-\left(\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{1}}\mathbf{v}+\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{p}}\mathbf{v}+\cdots+\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{p}}\mathbf{v}\right),\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle -\left\langle \text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{1}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle -\left\langle \text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{p}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle -\cdots-\left\langle \text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{p}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle -\left\langle \text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{j}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle -\left\langle \frac{\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{j},\mathbf{b}_{j}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{j},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle -\frac{\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{j}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{j},\mathbf{b}_{j}\rangle}\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{j},\mathbf{b}_{j}\right\rangle \\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,\ldots,p$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}-\text{proj}_{W}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

