\begin_layout Description
minimum
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

integer
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

solution 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ans:minimum-integer-solution"

\end_inset

We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $|(54x+30y)-17|$
\end_inset

 cannot equal zero, so the best we can hope for is to find integers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $|(54x+30y)-17|=1$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $(54x+30y)-17=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(54x+30y)-17=-1$
\end_inset

.
 Adding 17 to both sides of these equations, we seek integer solutions of
 
\begin_inset Formula $54x+30y=18$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $54x+30y=16$
\end_inset

.
 Since 16 is not a multiple of 6, there is no hope of finding integer solutions
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $54x+30y=16$
\end_inset

.
 Since 18 is a multiple of 6, perhaps there are integer solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $54x+30y=18$
\end_inset

.
 Dividing both sides of the equation by 6, 
\begin_inset Formula $9x+5y=3$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $9x=3-5y$
\end_inset

.
 As long as 
\begin_inset Formula $3-5y$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 9, we will have a solution.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-3$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $3-5y=18$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $9x=18$
\end_inset

), so one solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)=(2,-3)$
\end_inset

.
 Sure enough, 
\begin_inset Formula $|(54\cdot2+30\cdot-3)-17|=|108-90-17|=1$
\end_inset

.
 There are others.
\end_layout

